All scans were done using an identical process with 123D Catch.  The change from 3rd to 4th generation was so minimal that I chose to stop there.

title: Brushed 90mm Micro FPV Race Drone (SPRacing Evo, 8520 motors)

description.text:
I tried to design something that was ridged, durable and light. So far its taken a few pretty heavy crashes into concrete with no noticeable damage. This is my 3rd design and the one I am most happy with. Flight characteristics are great with very snappy cornering and good recovery from diving.

It has a 20 degree camera tilt which I find is perfect for these micros. If you're a new pilot this might be a little high but I find the wide viewing angle of these cams make the tilt less of an issue for new pilots.

Weight is 40g dead on. That is including a micro rx that I needed for my transmitter, newer flight controllers have onboard rx's that should bring the total weight down significantly. Wheelbase is 90mm.

I've also added a buzzer. I learned the hard way that leaving them off to save weight is a terrible idea if you plan on flying outdoors.

I've printed in pla, the only filament by cheep printer can handle. Abs might be a better option. I'd appreciate the feedback if you try it.

Parts list:
flight controller: spracing evo brushed
Motors: 8520 coreless
Camera: Not sure, its a standard micro cam vtx combo job. Any should fit no problem.
Props: Ladybirds
Buzzer: 5v buzzer
Misc: Foam tape for mounting the fc, rubber-bands

Build should be straightforward. Just use my photos for reference.

I highly recommend flashing the latest version of betaflight onto your flight controller. Instructions are a google away.

PIDS for bataflight:
These are the ones I found for the qx90 micro quad that is also a 90mm x frame. They seem to work very well.

p_pitch = 80
i_pitch = 45
d_pitch = 20
p_roll = 80
i_roll = 45
d_roll = 20
p_yaw = 75
i_yaw = 45

Credit to NJ tech for those

Updated for a bit more strength. Added about a gram of weight

EDIT
I've added a wip design that should be an improvement. Not fully tested yet. I'll keep uploading as the design changes

title: VESC 6 mount for TRAMPA Mountainboard
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
VESC 6 mount for Trampa Holypro 35.
It could fit to others models of Trampa boards (need the same mount drilling pattern).

You can either print the plate or use the drilling template.
On the pictures, I built a carbon fiber plate and used the drilling template.
2 versions of the plate : with or without hole for adding a heatsink.

The cover has 2 "windows" for RGB leds ring and stick, dimmed by a luminosity sensor (situated in center of the ring) connected to an Arduino.
The ring acts as battery gauge, the stick as rearlight/brakelight (behaves like car's rearlight).
For this purpose, the whole cover has been printed in transparent PETG with a thinner wall where the RGB leds are, then painted in black (see the post-printing process).

Please note that the STL part provided has no text on the cover.
But you can custom your text using the Solidworks file included.

VESC 6 have been mounted using heat paste (the same for CPU on computer).
In my opinion, this trick is not a good idea if you used a 3D-printed plate.

Enjoy !

Printer:

ZYYX+

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

40%

Notes:

Printed in transparent PETG.

After sanding with dry 180 sand paper, mask gauge and rearlight window before painting In order to protect the paint, I applied a thin layer of epoxy resin, sanded it with water-1000-sandpaper then applied another thin epoxy resin layer.

description.text:
Updated Rev 2 platform now has cutout for speaker audio to pass through. Since the KX2 has a rear facing speaker, I've had a few requests to make a hole in the platform. You only need to print one of the two platforms, and one of the legs. I am leaving the v1 of the platform incase someone doesn't want the cutout for the speaker.

This is a stand for the Elecraft KX2 radio. I based the two piece assembly (and collapsibility) off of the style used on an apparently discontinued KX3 stand, once manufactured by SOTAbeams. You will require some string and a plastic toggle spring stop (single hole) string cord lock - see photos.

The stand is meant to be easily disconnected, and broken down flat (for ease of transport in a backpack, for example).

On the second print, I used Simplify 3d, and 0.2 resolution and it came out just fine.

string and plastic toggle spring stop (single hole) string cord lock

title: Gearbox for turbo oven style coffee roaster

description.text:
This is the gearbox I put together using a slightly modified herringbone gear system from a wades extruder, for use as the agitator in a turbo oven coffee roaster.

All you need is
-a pair of 608zz bearings
-an M8 bolt (I used a 90mm bolt in my design), with a pair of nuts to lock the drive gear
-M8 washer between the 608zz bearing and the large gear
-NEMA 17 stepper motor.

I used an arduino nano to run a A4988 stepper driver that drove the stepper motor.

hope this is helpful for someone

Aquarium-Automation

Nice project for advanced makers, who have fishes nearby the soldering iron :-)

You need an arduino nano, a Wemos D1 mini (ESP8266), 4 buttons, a temperature sensor (
DS18B20), 3 Rela, a Neopixel like RGB-stripe, a frame, plexi-glas for the case.

This project offers:

  • Control LED-Light (Plants)
  • Coloured RGB-LEDs (Fore- & Background)
  • Pump Control
  • Temperature and alerting
  • Automatic Feeding
  • Minimizing cables around the aquarium
  • time planing for each feature
  • Control with webserver für PC and smartphone

A video ist better than 1000 words:
https://youtu.be/iqHUkQb2Dwk

I have divided the frame into two parts so i could print it on my Wanhao 5s mini.
If you have a printer with less building room, you have to divide it into more parts.

The printfiles with the round pads can be used to connect aluminum rods between them. They can be glued into aquarium's cover. Then you can bind the RGS stripes with cable ties into the cover.

If you are interested on the optional feeder engine (for nano granulates) please visit https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2437405

Have fun and greetings to the fishes, Nunz

Update: I have added an optional cooler, which can be easily connected to the USB-Ports which are integrated in the frame of this project:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2446884

description.text: Seattle Mini Maker Faire Robot Coin / Key FOB from "Thought to Thing in an Hour or Less" workshop at Seattle Mini Maker Faire June 2nd, 2012.

Seattle Mini Maker Faire Robot Coin / Key FOB from "Thought to Thing in an Hour or Less" workshop at Seattle Mini Maker Faire June 2nd, 2012.
Use the MakerFaireCoinDemoSingleColor_fixed.stl for single color prints
Use the MakerFaireCoinDemoColorOne_fixed.stl and MakerFaireCoinDemoColorTwo_fixed.stl for 2 Color Prints from machines like the Makerbot Replicator.
I've posted the proccess we went through during the "Thought to Thing" workshop to design and print the Maker Faire Robot Coin here. http://wulfdesign.blogspot.com/2012/06/seattle-mini-maker-faire-robot-coin-key.html
I've included all the design files from start to finish, including the original Maker Faire Robot image (probably Copywrite and Trademark of Maker Faire).
This is actually Version 2 from doing up the documentaion for posting. It should work the same or better than the originals we did up during the workshop, but if not let me know and I can upload them as well.
The workshop version was designed to be only 2mm thick for quick printing due to time constraints and for give away during the Maker Faire. I'll try and upload a beefier 3mm version that'll hold up better as well as a version with a beveled draft that can be cast up in metal easily.
As always it was a lot of fun coming up with something and seeing it printed in such a short amount of time. 2 Color 3d printing has come a long way in the past couple of years. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4219
A Special thanks to Emmett and his Makerbot Replicator [Venus] for being on hand to make the 2 Color Printing possible. http://www.thingiverse.com/emmett

author: olskar

description.text:
This spoilboard has been designed to mate with the T slots on a 1325 Chinese CNC router. The router has 6 independent vacuum sections, and there is one spoilboard for each section.

It should be cut out of 18mm MDF. I got lucky and found some 2700x1000x18mm boards that were used for packaging for AUD$2/sheet.

The board mounts with M8 bolts to the bed, and provides 30 M5x10 threaded inserts for workholding. Both the bolts and inserts are recessed to allow the board to be resurfaced a few times before discarding. If used on a vacuum table, both sides should be surfaced and the edges sealed. This allows the sections of the vacuum table to operate independently.

There's a 10 minute video of the board being cut here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Y0ol5MrMvU

The model is in Fusion 360, and most things have been parameterised for easy customisation. I've added an STL to keep thingiverse happy, but seriously, don't 3D print your spoilboard :)

title: Hictop Dual Extrusion with mostly stock parts

description.text:
I bought a few Hictop Prusa i3s (3DP-11) and replaced the hotends on two of them with E3D V6s. Because of this I had some stock parts left over, and before throwing them in a box, I got to playing around with them and realized it would be quite easy to upgrade these stock parts to dual extrusion.

The only catch of this system is that it requires Bowden extruders. However, these are quite easy to print and assemble or to purchase directly. I used this one:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1318849

If you want to maximize the use of stock parts you could try this one:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2070374

Basic steps:

  1. Take everything off the X-carriage.

  2. Print one of the "jigs". These are based off of the x-carriages that I had (so your mileage might vary), but the idea is that this will line up the spots you need to drill. Use a punch or something else to mark the holes.

  3. Drill the two holes in the carriage (6 mm). Along with drilling the holes, I opened up the heat break hole. The reason for doing this is that it allows you to fully remove the new hotend by simply removing the one M6 bolt that holds on the aluminum block. You'll want to orient the new hotend so the heater and thermistor wires come out toward the right front so you can remove that bolt.

  4. Print out the hotend Bowden blocks. These are designed to be tapped for M6 PTFE couplers. You'll need one standard and one that is mirrored.

  5. Put X-carriage back on.

  6. Rewire everything. You'll need to connect a stepper motor at E1, the E1 heater, fan, and thermistor. Hictop uses JST-XHP connectors for the motor and thermistor on their control boards.

  7. Adjust nozzle height. This can be tricky. I setup everything on the left extruder and slowly lowered it onto a pre-leveled glass build plate, while leaving the right nozzle and heat break loose in the aluminum block. The tricky part is tightening the set screw. The threads on the heatbreak make the whole assembly want to go up or down a little bit. Try twisting things slightly til you have the set screw tightened and both of the nozzles are just touching the build plate.

  8. Determine your offset. There may be both X and Y offset. In my case, everything was lined up very nicely in Y and the X offset was ~35 mm. You can get a rough estimate with calipers and get exact numbers with some test prints.

  9. Update firmware. I'll give you a link to mine shortly (latest Marlin). Note, you'll likely have to make modifications to the E-steps.

  10. Print some stuff.

https://youtu.be/ImFsGOO7b-8

Major upgrade

New ways of managing the files to simplify understanding !
Some parts were deleted because without interest

Upgrade Majeur

Nouvelle manière de gérer les dossiers afin de simplifier la compréhension !
Certaine pièce ont étaient supprimées car sans interet

English

I noticed that some inserts had to work in traction, this new sadness I have decided to make this upgrade so that all tightening work in compression (no risk of pulling)

Upgrade X XY And Z carriage with the addition of Clamp for the Bearing.
I remain available for any interesting evolutions. Let's make our printers together!

Thanks !

Upgrade for M3 Nut Mount

  • X Carriage and XY Carriage for LM8UU, LM8LUU, LM10UU, LM10LUU, or Igus Ø8 Int Ext 15.4 and 16.2mm
  • Extruder Mount for E3D V6 + BL Touch https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2366952
  • Z Carriage For LM12UU

All internal dimensions are provided with 0.2 to 0.4 in addition to this to simplify the assembly

All mounting dimensions (Standards Versions) are identical to the original version the parts are therefore compatible. This is not the case for the reinforced version

The XY carriage and the Clamp can also be mounted with the insert or M3 nuts

Français

J'ai remarqué que certains inserts devaient travailler en traction, j'ai décidé de faire cette mise à niveau pour que tout serrage travail en compression (Risque d'arrachement en traction)

Améliorez le chariot de X XY et de Z avec l'addition de la bride pour le roulement.
Je reste disponible pour toute évolution intéressante. Faisons nos imprimantes ensemble!

Mon imprimante étant en enceinte, je développe actuellement une double chaîne de câbles que je posterais une fois terminée elle est fixée à l'arrière sur X Chariot

Merci !

Mise à niveau pour le montage de l'écrou M3

  • Chariot X et Chariot XY pour LM8UU, LM8UUU, LM10UU, LM10UUU ou Igus Ø8 Int Ext 15,4 et 16,2 mm
  • Support d'extrudeuse pour E3D V6 + BL Touch https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2366952
  • Z chariot pour LM12UU

Toute les cotes intérieur sont prévue avec 0.2 à 0.4 en plus ceci afin de simplifier le montage

Toutes les dimensions de montage (versions de normes) sont identiques à la version d'origine, les pièces sont donc compatibles. Ce n'est pas le cas pour la version renforcée

Le chariot XY et la pince peuvent également être montés avec l'insert ou les écrous M3

Printer:

Anet A6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

40%

Notes:

ABS: 5 perimeter 6 bottom 6 top solid layer

description.text:
This is based on the rebelix part:
https://github.com/RepRap4U/RebeliX

However, my frame's profile is different, so I fixed the problems in the scad which made the customization difficult. I've also removed the dependencies to other scads. (and replaced the czech comments with english)

The part includes a support for the plastic which goes to the slot, you might want this removed if your can manually place supports in your slicer.

The uploaded STL is set up for my profile (3030 with 6mm slot and M5 screws) It also includes the support set up for .2mm layer height.

remixed_from.title: 380mm Long Twin Jet Drive Work Boat

title: Single Screw work boat (in progress, not finished)

description.text:
2017 07 23: applied putty twice, painted twice (not sure if it was worth doing so) and applied yacht lacquer. Buoyancy seems just fine, 2,5 kg is a the limit. Hopefully, all the components will be lighter.

2017 07 20: bottom part is glued and it's a nightmare. Especially the front end. Next on the to do list is a lot of grinding, applying putty, polishing and eventually some adequate water insulation. Haven't decided on that yet should I stick to marine lacquer or glass fiber with epoxy. Anyhow, it's nice thing to make, but not suitable for mass production.

Ok, this is just a very start and it's not ready for sure. All credtis go to Lewis, I just used his work and modified in my way.

Since I'm not a big fan of glueing, a lot is done by interlocking parts therefore ir you will use any other thickness of plywood than 3 mm, you will have some issues. So use at your own risk.

Up to now some tricks and hints: for sides - soak them in watter for 20 minutes before bending. Also mind patern of the tree as one way it bends, other - breaks.

Components, intended to be used for this boat:

RX/TX:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Original-High-Quality-GoolRC-TG3-2-4GHz-3CH-Digital-Radio-Remote-Control-Transmitter-with-Receiver-for/32701262620.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

Steering rudder:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Original-Feilun-FT009-7-Feilun-Steering-Rudder-Spare-Part-for-Feilun-FT009-RC-Boat/32795487051.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

Servo for steering:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Professional-RC-Car-Spare-Part-Robot-Servo-S3003-Boat-Plane-Vehicle-Power-Standard-Servo-SUV-Steering/32793163584.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

Brushed motor with 4 x 100 mm shaft and screw:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-Shipping-380-boat-motor-with-shaft-Propeller-kit-shaft-assembly-spare-parts-for-DIY-RC/32742987290.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

ESC:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1pcs-Original-Hobbywing-Eagle-20A-ESC-For-Brushed-Motor-For-RC-Airplane-Plane-370-380-390/32371909564.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

Batteries:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/4pcs-lot-EAIEP-100-2100mAh-3-7V-li-Ion-ICR18650-21F-Rechargeable-18650-Batteries-mobile-power/32807481704.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

Battery box:
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/2017-free-shipping-hot-sale-Plastic-Battery-Storage-Case-Box-Holder-For-3-x-18650-Black/32811468125.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.0zuk3r

I'm new to RC things to if you have advices you are more than welcome to advise me.

remixed_from.title: Prusa I3 MK2 Raspberry Pi Camera Mount

title: Prusa MK2 / ELP cam Bed Mount

description.text:
Instead of using a Raspberry Pi camera with my Prusa MK2/Octoprint system, I'm actually using a ELP USB wide angle full HD camera (http://www.elpcctv.com). I prefer an USB one simply because it allows me to use it with other devices.

I got inspired by this by https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2113975 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1646474 for the base design.

The bed arm could be installed on the two side of the Prusa bed and can be moved forward or backward. The back cover could be installed in different orientations, so you could bring out the USB cable from the case on the side you want. As the front and back case parts close very very tightly, I have added 2 small apertures to easily open the case with a small screwdriver. As the camera heats I have also added apertures for aeration.

The case is fixed on the arm using a M3x25 screw + nuts. Amd the arm is fixed on the Prusa bed using a M3x10 screw + washer.

description.text:
This is a 'Global' dice-counter, and Day/Night keeper for the Talisman boardgame with 'Blood Moon' expansion. Holds two D6's.
We place it with the rounded edge to the board, and the square part to the one keeping an eye on the game-flow.
It allows 2 simultaneaous counters, to keep track of turns for an event involving multiple players, f.e.
You place the card in the holder, turn the pointer of the dice holder to the player that triggered the event, and start counting..
It also has a slot in front of the Day/Night switch, it allows you to put a card in it, that should be discarded when dawn/dusk appears, f.e.

For this design I used tree things:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1939478

  • Used stone texture

AND

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:764352

  • Used dice holder
  • Cleaned & closed bottom
  • Added hole in center and pin to match

AND

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2341075

  • Used card Slot profile

I made a 'Night' and a 'Day' 3D object of the original card-design. These go into a holder.
Designed the hole and pin. Tested rotation. Then I made the base to keep it all together.

-PrintStuff-
You might want to print Day/Night in different colors.
Print the Diceholder twice.
No supports needed.
for Cura, enable 'Expand skins into infill' preference. (to avoid holes where walls meet.)
Tested print on Prusa MKII.

-Assembly-
Diceholders: First put pin through hole in bottom of the dice-holder. Then use a dice inside it, to press it into the hole in the base.
Day-Night: The Day/Night Holder has small print-supports that needs to be removed. Use plyer or cutter. You can glue the '3D cards' in the slots of the holder. Then push down the lot on the pin in the middle of the base. (you might need to do a run-in, by turning it a few times left and right, so it slides more easily.)

I can only say how gratefull I am that people share stuff so others can change it. So if you're keen to that principle, don't go making money on what people share for free !

-Enjoy-

I wanted to have a touch screen LCD that is set up in the same manner as a cell phone, with the digitizer adhered to the frame. title: Necklace hanger
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a hanger able to hold 14 necklaces (or other suitable staff such as wristbands). Print supports are necessary, however, two hangers have been designed out of the body in order to only use bed supports to obtain a better quality print. Moreover, dual hangers help not to swing once placed on bar.

To use it, place heavier and longer necklaces in middle positions of both sides, then, place other necklaces in subsequent positions of both sides in order not to unbalance the hanger (it's difficult to unbalance it placing necklaces in ramdon positions, this is only a recommendation).

This thing only requires about 20 grams of filament, the mine one has been printed as follows:
-Print position as shown in images.
-0.2 mm of layer height: this value guarantees that upper hanger union is properly printed without using additional supports. Obviously this configuration will depend on your printer bridge quality.
-Infill 50 % with PLA will ensure enough robustness (you can print it in ABS, but probably it would need higher infill rate)
-Only bed supports with a 50º angle and 50 % of density (these are CURA parameters, you can use equivalent parameters according to your slicer). If you don't mind to use more supports or even onto the body try to use them, my configuration minimizes the filament and print duration, however it could be a good practice to assure the printing.
-Of course, a proper retraction setting for your printer/filament is highly recommended to improve print quality, as always.

In case you have any doubt or suggestion, please comment!

Hope you enjoy!

ANET A6

Doesn't Matter

author: yoghi85

description.text:
Do you like GTA 5, have 2 spools of black filament, and 84 hours to spare? Well, why don't you print the railgun? this is a 1:1 scale of the railgun that can be acquired in story mode and some online missions. It has a removable mag and can light up with theses lights: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00EZMGHLU/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1. I just wound the EL wire up and down both sides until all the rail was covered. To paint the rails I just covered up the black parts with painters tape and used silver spray paint to paint the center. The fit for the wire might be a little tight but I found if you remove the clip on the back and file out some of the holes it fits nicely. Finally, I used a bolt for the stock adjustment.

If you do print this please post a picture, ill love to see it.

author: Ouistiti

description.text: to use as flexible cable guide, to protect cables to moving parts.

This is my first attempt at making anything printable, and a way to teach myself about Inventor.  It still needs some work, but I'm done wasting plastic on cups for a while.  
This collapsible cup is about the size of a shot glass, when extended.  Its collapses down to less than 3/4" and expands to just over 1 1/2" tall.  
It prints as one piece.  The outer layers have to be cleaned up on the bottom edge after printing. 
The handle is pretty weak, I think my next version will have a beefier handle.  
Printed on a Replicator.

Print it solid, otherwise it will leak.  
No raft or Support needed!  All the support necessary is built into the model.  
NOTE TO THING-O-MATIC USERS:  You will probably need to scale this up to get a good print.  The cup walls are too close together, and it wont print solid.

remixed_from.author: pieterbos82
remixed_from.title: The PrintBone: a fully printable playable trombone

title: PrintBone small - 7 inch bell trombone
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The PrintBone, a 3D printed trombone. Now in 7 inch bell version with 12mm bore slide. Designed with the help of acoustic modelling software. Comes with carbon fiber slide, complete with PLA stockings.

Also available in large bore version at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2252952

It plays like a nice and bright small bore trombone. It doesn't play as loud as some 8 inch bell/.500 inch slide brass trombones, but it's bright enough to be heard without playing too loud. It plays in tune with the included slide. I've gotten the slide action to be OK, but not great. Brass bushings instead of PLA stockings will greatly improve slide action. With the PLA stockings, use trombone slide cream, not slide-o-mix or yamaha slide lubricant - they will not work well.

The outer slide is very light and can be used as a Bach 42 outer slide. Measured to the width of my bach 42 slide, it may be different on yours. If you've only used brass slide, you'll be surprised. At under 100 grams, the slide action is simply amazing if you get it aligned well.

Fits a Conn 48H/6H/Director slide and bell. With a Conn 48H slide, the third partial (F in first position) plays a bit higher than in most trombones. This may take some getting used to.

what you need:

  • A 3D-printer with an at least 18x18cm print bed, 20cm high
  • 2x 15mm ID/16MM OD carbon fiber tubes, about 70-75cm
  • 2x 12mm ID/14MM OD carbon fiber tubes, about 70-75cm
  • about half a roll of PLA
  • cyanoacrylate glue, eg super glue
  • sandpaper, I used 150, 320 and 600 grit
  • trombone slide cream (not slide-o-mix or yamaha lubricant)
  • tuning slide grease
  • a small shank mouthpiece - metal, plastic or 3d printed

Should cost about €70-100 in materials, mainly due to the high cost of carbon fiber tubes. I used http://www.s2-carbon.com/rohre/glaenzend/17/carbon-rohr-16-x-15-x-1000-mm-glanz?c=9 for the outer tubes and https://hobbyking.com/en_us/carbon-fiber-tube-hollow-14x750mm.html for the inner tubes. The hobbyking inners are incorrectly listed as 14x13, but are actually 14x12mm, as I found out after receiving them. If they happen to be 14x13, that will work, although you might want a larger leadpipe in that case.

Printing the bell

Print parts of bell. The bell flare will need support, and the part that includes the slide receiver as well. The other parts do not require support.
Use at least 40% infill for the bracing, more means a stiffer trombone and it should still be very light.

Assembling the bell

Find all leaks by using a brush with dishwashing detergent. Seal one end of each part, then blow in the other end - if there are bubbles there's a leak! Fix with some glue.
Sand the connectors so they fit smoothly together.

Now sand the tuning slide until it fits into the trombone. Do NOT force it, the tuning slide pegs are quite fragile. When it fits, apply tuning slide grease - it will slide in much easier and it will make an airtight seal.
Now glue the bell section together. Start by applying glue to the inside of the top brace. Hold top part of neckpipe plus top part of bell together. Now insert the tuning slide and wait until the glued is dried a little.
Now practice putting the next two parts together on the trombone without glue.
Then apply glue on the inside of the bottom brace, and the top joints of both the neckpipe bottom part and middle bell part. Apply a thin layer of glue to the outside and inside all around to ensure an airtight seal, or it will leak.
Now glue the two parts at the same time to the already assembled part. Having someone else hold the top part can be useful here, but it can be done with just two hands.
Glue the bell flare by applying glue on the connector - again, thing layer of glue on the inside and outside of the connector!

Printing the slide

Print parts of the slide. Use 50-100% infill on the handgrips for extra stiffness, especially on the inner slide grip. You should need support for the inner slide grip only.
Print the leadpipe standing upright.
Check all parts for leaks again and fix or reprint at slower speed.

The parts are matched to the specific tubes I ordered, so they might not fit your tubes. In that case, go to http://github.com/pieterbos/PrintBone and fit to your own tubes with OpenSCAD.

Assembling the slide

Fit stockings around the smaller tubes. The stockings should go at the end of the inner slide. Sand stockings so they are very smooth and fit smoothly in the outer tubes. This might take quite a bit of sanding, so sand, check if it moves smoothly, repeat, until you have a working slide. Do not overdo it, the slide will leak if you sand too much material away - you can always fix this later.
Glue the stockings after checking the slide action and checking the airtightness of the slide. Use just a drop of glue, or the glue will add to the thickness of the stockings and you need to sand off more.

The key to a good working slide is very good alignment. The tubes should be perfectly parallel. Check this at every point before applying any glue.

Cut the outer slide tubes to desired length.
Now assemble outer slide and inner slide. Do not yet glue. Check if everything moves smoothly and alignment is correct. If so, glue outer slide crook and handgrip to tubes while it is around the inner tubes, including the inner handgrip. Ensure they are straight and parallel!
Cut inner slides to correct length. Mark the length while inserted into slide grip, do NOT make them both the same length.
You can use the half outer slide grip, or the one with the whole tubes. Half is lighter, but much harder to assemble with correct alignment.

Now glue the inner slide tubes to the handgrip while partially inserted in the outer slide. Ensure they are perfectly parallel and move smoothly.

Insert leadpipe and mouthpiece. You're done!

Playtesting

It should sound like a trombone. If instead it sounds fuzzy/plasticy, worse on some notes than others, you probably have a leak somewhere. You can find and fix it and it should improve.

Brass trombone compatibility

The PrintBone small fits several regular trombone parts:

  • The outer slide fits a Bach 42B inner slide. This bell will NOT fit. It will make for a very light outer slide - unlike any brass slide! Parts may need adjustment based on width variations of different slides. It plays and sounds well, but a 14.9mm tube would be even better for this purpose.

  • The inner slide fits a bach 42 outer slide, if you sand the stockings a bit more. however, it will be a strange combination
  • The slide fits a A Conn 48H/6H bell, and some Conn director bells. It will be a bit brighter than the regular slide on a 48H/6H.
  • The bell fits A Conn 48H/6H slide, but you will need to extend the tuning slide quite a bit.

3D printing. Organizer. Printing on a mirror (glass)

This is the closest thing to a mechanical mod I can print. Simple, easy to print personal vaporizer, with very little parts count. The switch is made of brass strips and the spring is the deformation of the case. This works perfectly. It's uses an 18650 lithium battery. Use an AWIMR battery with protection circuit, for safety.
I added a locking switch that slides a Mylar strip between the contact to make it pocket safe. I made the walls thicker and added reinforcements to the screw pins. I just printed it out without support or raft on my Da Vinci 1.0 printer at normal setting and it worked like a charm..

I printed it with PLA with 50 % infill and full support. It's easy to clean up since the support is very small.
You will need 3, #4 X 3/4" wood screws countersink a small amount of #16 wire and some .5mm brass shim stock.
You will also need a ecig. connector or a 510 to 510 adapter or an Ego to 510 adapter.
I put in a print of the template for cutting the brass and another for bending the switch pate.

comments.text: I made this mod but I am not showing the make. The protection button doesn't fit in the hole and it's pointless anyways. I drilled the hole bigger to fit a floating pin 510 connector, it totally wipes out the need for the positive lead. Which worked out to hold the battery better because it pushes on the upper battery terminal. Other batteries work if you stick a penny under the top battery connection. The screw holes are too small for the screws specified. You have to drill them bigger and use #4 5/8, 3/4 are too long. The templates didn't work out for me either. I used .1mm brass instead of .5 mm, accidently got the wrong one but it worked just fine. I used solid brass instead of soldering wires to it. I did both sides with a thin strip and cut the ends like a hook around the 510 and then tightened the nut so it was secure on the brass and the body of the mod. Works great. What I don't like about it is that the battery gets pushed too much into the mod from squeezing it and sometimes you have to readjust it. The screw holes are in bad places. The firing lever shows a split in it because there is only that one screw at the bottom. The top screw needs moving because it makes the plastic split under the 510. And yes I know I altered that part, but who uses a e-cig connector anymore anyways. I know the split is from the pressure. What would be awesome is if someone can take this principle and make it a dual 18650 or a single 26650. Enclose the battery, no protection switchy thing (no mechanical I know uses one) I bet you could even make a dos equis style 3d printed model/ style one. But all in all this is a great little mod. I just wish it was heftier, more battery and take today's connectors. With the current design it looks like something I would have used about 5 years ago with a carto. And I have been vaping for 8 years now.

remixed_from.author: Redbrumbler
remixed_from.title: Nintendo Switch joy-con grip (now with a rework!)

description.text:
I've tried several different JoyCon grips on this site and none of them fit well. I remixed this one to use the least amount of material possible, but still be sturdy enough. The fit should be snug, without needing too much force to connect the JoyCons. You may have to hold the release button down to slide them back out.

My remix changes include removing the top and bottom of the model and chamfering the edges so that the JoyCon slides on easier.

*Update 1: I've added a new model with the tops of each channel rounded off. This makes it easier to use, since you don't have to worry about it sliding to far.

*Update 2: In case you are having an issue with the scale, you can use this info. to correct it in which ever slicer you're using:
For the closed top version, Cura gives me these dimensions:
Size X: 15mm, Size Y: 57.165mm, Size Z: 31.973mm
For the open top version, Cura gives me:
Size X: 15mm, Size Y: 57.165mm, Size Z: 29.216mm
Changing one of the dimensions should automatically update the others to keep the same scale.

Printer: MonoPrice MP Select Mini 3D Printer
Settings:
-Fill Density: 15%
-Layer Height: 0.2mm
-Support: Not needed

Make sure that there is no extra material around the bottom edge of either channel (where the Joycon's slide in) after printing. This would make it harder to slide in the controllers.

comments.text: I love it! it's actually the first one that was made to fit! Only remark I might have is that the closed one could maybe be more integrated with the looks of the joycon itself (shape and where it ends or something) I might look into remixing it :P

This is my first real attempt at '3D Printed ART'

I saw a sculpture in a 'designer' store, and although I (and my partner) relay liked it.
The price tag was ridiculous !!

Looking at it i wrote the OPEN-SCAD then and there, in my head..
Although the one in the shop was not segmented.

I printed this in two parts,
although, I should of put the join (the overlap) down on the print bead.

As far as finishing it:
I used some Milliput, to fill in the join,
and a coat of primer.

then acrylic paint.

I will be printing another, much larger, but in one piece,
and allow Cura to make supports,

I was very impressed with the supports generated, by cura.

they snapped off easily, and minimal marking,
It would of been better, if I had turned down the temperature a little,

Milliput to fill in the gaps/floors

I found that after pushing the filler into the gaps,
I wet my fingers, and molded it into shape.

Sanded, primer, sanding

Painting.

Open SCAD

This is made from a series of a simple shapes,
swepped in i circular path, whilst being rotated by 90 Degrees.

and copious use of hull().

description.text:
GoPro Plastic Bottle Cap Mount
The idea is to use any plastic bottle as a grip/stand/floaty at the same time.
I saw plenty of solutions here on Thingiverse as well, but I did not find any of them perfect.
The concept is brilliant, you get basically a free GoPro grip, which at the same time makes your camera float. Though a 3D print is most likely not 100% watertight, it is good enough to make your GoPro float in water.

I designed it 3D-print friendly, but also with common engineering sense:

  • no need for supports, the big inner overhang is sloped
  • sharp edges are rounded: especially important in high stress areas
  • also the edges sitting on the printbed are smoothened: they could cut your hand otherwise when tightening the cap
  • walls are thick enough that some infill will be printed to get a sturdy part (two other prints I tried from the site where bendy, weak)
  • yet tried to keep size to the minimum not to get a bulky part
  • surface is grooved to create better grip

I used the standard thread called PCO1881. This is the newer style - lightweight and lower profile, against the older PCO1810. Outside diameter is 27.4 mm and pitch is 2.7 mm.

The drawing was printed, used and tested diving in a lake with the GoPro Session and I was satisfied with it.
I hope you will enjoy it!

title: EPIC FAIL FIAL | fridge magnet (image macro meme letters)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Miserably failing magnet. Put it on your fridge, door, broken car, printer or your ex-boyfriend's picture .. what NOT can you use it for?!

Possible as a two colour print with a filament swap. The letters have a hole in the back that fits a magnet with a diameter of 12mm and a thickness of 3mm, which I happened to have lying around.
Do a filament swap at z-height 4mm to get a nice two colour magnet. For the rest it's a very simple and easy print. To add the magnet, adding a dash of glue is recommended.
First made the lettering and outlines as two SVG files in Illustrator and then brought them together in Tinkercad, where I also added the hole for the magnet

title: K8200 Titan Aero Mount with integrated BLTouch Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
With this thing, you mount an E3D Titan Aero (TM) to your K8200 (TM).
The smaller BLTouch (TM) mount is optional.

Because the full assembly is mounted below the z axis profile, the hot-end is a bit lower than with other settings (so you might lose 10mm of your total build height), but it is very stable and the filament feed and tensioner are quite well accessible.

The whole mount slides diagonally over the aluminum bar in a 45-degree angle (no breakable snap-in).

I added an adjustable mount for the BLTouch sensor, which is not perfect but keeps the sensor as near to the nozzle as possible. Thus it interferes a bit with the big extruder gear, but a 1.5mm clearance is built it.

Disclaimer: This is work in progress. I have not installed mine yet, as I'll have to design a new fan duct first, as the stepper is in the way.

Printer:

K8200 (heavily modified)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Prints find w/o support.

The main assembly is straightforward with four M5 bolts and square nuts.

The small BLTouch adapter is a bit fiddly; you first have to insert the two M3 hex-nuts holding the BLTouch. The fitting is very tight, so the nuts stay in place. Only one of the holes of the bigger adapter used. The lower face of the mount (i.e. the top face of the BLTouch) should be about 44.5mm above the nozzle tip.
I used onshape.com to design it. It allows for designing a new part in the context of already existing parts, which is a killer feature for all kinds of mounts.

title: Cooling Blower for Smartrapcore Alu
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is the cooling blower mount I've been using with pretty good success with the Smartrapcore Alu printer. It is specifically fit with no adjustment as primarily I was having issues of it falling down over time. Pair this with a standard blower to get a pretty decent air stream across the nozzle exit of an E3D V6 hotend.

CAUTION: This is very close to the E3D V6 hotend heater block and therefore requires the use of an E3D silicon sock. Without the silicon sock, the hotend will melt and deform the cooling blower.

The flag on top of the blower is being used as an attachment point for all my hotend cabling.

I was hesitant to publish this design considering it's highly customized and fit against my exact printer build that uses my E3D Titan Direct Drive for Smartrapcore. There is also another version I'm using that works with my Flexion for E3D Retrofit kit for E3D Hotend for Smartrapcore thing which is longer due to the different position of the hotend nozzle.

title: Dominion Box Insert
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This design is an insert for dominion, that I can house 4 large expansions/base games in one box. The design is fairly modular so it can be modified as desired.

It is extremely important to make sure the printed parts are very flat. If there is any warping, the pieces will not interlock properly. I highly recommend optimizing the print process for one piece. The optimized parameters should work for all the remaining pieces. On my personal printer, a skirt helped quite significantly.

In order to create a layout similar to the sample pictures, you will need to print the following:
4 x Piece 1
4 x Piece 2
4 x Piece 3
2 x Piece 4
2 x Piece 5
2 x Piece 6
2 x Piece 7
2 x Piece 8

Pieces 1, 2, and 3 all combine into one long piece (you should end up with 4 long pieces, all the same length and size; make sure to not swap any of these pieces for 4, 5, or 6)(feel free to glue if necessary; on my printer, the joints are tight enough that friction holds them in place). The 4 long pieces from 1, 2, and 3 will form the exterior square of the insert.
Pieces 4, 5, and 6 all combine into another long piece. The 2 long pieces from 4, 5, and 6 can be place inside of the framework formed above. This should create three rectangular storage areas. I would recommend place these long pieces such that the two exterior areas are exactly the height of a card. This arrangement will allow you to store 4 expansions in the box (2 on each side) and use the middle section for various cards and pieces.
Pieces 7 and 8 can then be used to create further storage areas, separating the long rectangular areas into smaller areas. Depending on the placement of pieces 4, 5, and 6, you may need to modify the dimensions of pieces 7 and 8.

XYZ da Vinci Mini

No

Others have made something like this, so I figured I'd give my take on the subject. It's kind of cheesy though since there's no specification to it. So far just something to hold 6 magnets and a part that the windings would go on. The rest I'll have to come up with later.

--- Edit ---
Added a casing piece. Two of those might do it, but if not - I'll have to make the other casing half different for wires and stuff.

Obviously it's going to need wiring, bearings, magnets, and fasteners. Not so obvious is the nubs (or lack thereof) on the stator indicate winding groups, and holes through the stator parts are for putting string through to help anchor the windings. Rest is brushless motor stuff which I'm sure you can google and figure out on your own. No specs, so this is for experimenting and messing around.

title: 3D Printer belt tension measuring tool for small 3D printers like Renkforce RF100

description.text:
This tool is based on an idea by user calviniba https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2230598

Update 21.07.2017: Remade all STL files, because Thingiview won't render them for 3D view. SketchUp files included.

I made a complete new and compacter design (not a remix), small enough for Renkforce RF100 which has a steel body before the belt. That makes it difficult to measure the belt tension, so I created this one. But it should work with other printers, too.

The biggest difference is that this tool uses a standard ball pen spring with 3mm diameter. I tried to print the 2,4mm shaft, but that didn't work and broke down. So I decided to use the ball pen mine itself as shaft.

First put the spring on the other side of the mine. Than cut it as shown at the pictures. Beware of ink, better use a ball pen mine that is empty.

Use super or plastic glue to assemble.

Last you need 3 M3 screws. On my model I glued them in, so there is no hex nut needed.

Every ball pen spring is other. Before you disassemble your printer, measure the old tension and use a pen to mark the positions on the tool. Both sides should have nearly the same tension, so only one line is needed. If not, use different colors to mark the position.

Printer:

RF100

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm and 0.2mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Main body and knob can be printed well with 0.2mm layers. For the slider use 0.1mm layer. Rotate the slider 90 degrees for printing (hole at the bottom). If the slider stocks at the body after printing, sand it a little bit.

You need to assemble: 1 ball pen mine
1 ball pen spring 3mm
3 screws M3x16
some glue

remixed_from.author: klownius
remixed_from.title: Anet A8 Motor Mount Replacement (with Z Axis REAL Fix)

title: Zonestar P802qr2 motor mount Z axis

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1lsOqybtPPp

I took Simhopp's Replacement Motor Mount, and I adjusted it for Zonestar p802qr2 metal.
I took Adjustable Z-Axis Motor Mount by djnicolosi3148,and I adjusted it for Zonestar p802qr2 metal.
I took Anet A8 motor mount fix by klownius,and I adjusted it for Zonestar p802qr2.

Also, A big thanks to Simhopp, djnicolosi3148, klownius for doing this!

I printed this using ABS and 40% infill .14 HOURS PRINTING TIME.

Klownius took Simhopp's Replacement Motor Mount, and adjusted it so that it has slotted (oval) screw holes for the four motor screws. Also, I adjusted the motor hole so that it is also slotted (oval). Each Z Axis motor can be slid to the left or right. This should straighten up those threaded rods and allow the Z carriages to slide up and down smoothly.

Now, it is possible to reprint the carriages on either side so that they straighten up the Z threaded rod, too. They can still be used with this mod to tweak it just right. And replacing that fragile acrylic is always a good thing (I keep mine as spares).

Klownius measured the center of the threaded rod to the center of the non threaded rod on each side. I now have 23mm on top and bottom for BOTH sides, so I know they are pretty parallel.

(They can bear weight if tilting the printer). I pounded the top plate onto each side plate with a rubber mallet, and I screwed them together (tight parts fit = no vibration). Then, each mount box slid right into the frame, no issue, no mallet, no anything. It is an easy replacement, but it took a little bit of fiddling to get the axis perfect straight. Also, I installed a cork gasket over each motor to help with vibration.

Each mount was three separate pieces (rather than one single piece), and this was done for two reasons:
1) Strength of materials - long thin layers on the side walls are more brittle than a large layered area.
2) If your Z Axis is really bad BUT at least can print under about 10mm (probably closer to 8mm), you can print this (still need good X and Y axis).

Work in progress . It's on my ZONESTAR P802QR2 right now.

Here is a link to the motor gaskets so that you know what I am talking about:
http://www.makergeeks.com/ne17stga4pa.html

The originals motor mount:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1474131
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2170852
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1214772
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:910140

Also, a big thanks to Simhopp, djnicolosi3148, klownius for doing this!

description.text:
A pet toy with a steel ball bearing inside. It makes noises, and rolls around in a neat way. The ball bearings I have are 11.11mm, but anything larger will work as well.

You don't press the bearing through, you drop it inside DURING the print. Carefully set however many bearings you like into the shell while it's at 50-70% completion. Remember that the hot-end is hot and that you don't want to place the bearing until it sits below the current layer (otherwise it might collide).

With a small magnet you can combine 2 or more toys so they spin around differently.

title: Anet A2 Y-Axis front cable chain bracket

description.text:
This bracket is designed for Anet A2 in order to mount the cable chain to the hotbed acrylic frame when you have the connector in front/read position. (Especially useful for 220x270 hotbed size)
I consider it as an extension of the very well designed cable chain for the Tevo Tarantula printer by Alejandrosnz: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2006671, from where you can get the frame bracket and the chain components.
Cables can be pulled out from the left squared hole or from the top if over-sized.
Better to print it in ABS to avoid any bending due to the hotbed high temperature. (PLA is also good if your bed is isolated)

How to fix the chain to the printer

To fix the frame bracket to the Anet A2, you need just a M4 screw and T-nut.
To fix the extension to the hotbed acrylic frame you can use glue or M3 screw with nut.

  • Put the nut inside the connector and the screw from the outside.
  • Set the bracket on the acrylic frame and tighten the screw. No drilling is required.

title: Car holder for Samsung Galaxy S7, and HTC Desire 620

description.text:
Holders are designed to be joined together with 6mm aluminium rods. Rods should be attached to you obsolete navigation holder with screws or zipties.
Galaxy S7 with back cover has the same thickness as HTC without cover, so both slide nicely.
Left side exposes light sensors, otherwise phone would switch to minimum brightness (when automatic brightness mode is enabled). There is also cutout for speaker.
Righ side exposes S7 home button, microphone, another speaker, and micro USB connector for charging.
I printed both sides without supports - they are designed for efficient bridging with vertical walls and continuous top cover between them.
Be careful when attaching right side to rods. I immediately broke upper part. This may be considered feature since now back button of S7 is also exposed, and wall is needed to print right edge :)

comments.text:
I have a "Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus" printer. I tray many models for Spool holder but most of them have the same "problem"....they are made by "plastic" materials and the spool / drum is made by "plastic" ....so the friction between those materials are big , no matter what size / shape you made it the spool holder .
That's way I decided to make a spool holder based on ball Bearings .
I bought 4 x Rubber sealed Bearing Size: 6200 2RS 10x30x9mm 62002RS ( http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/6200-2RS-to-6208-2RS-Rubber-Sealed-Bearings-Choose-Size-6200RS-6208RS/131116830076?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&var=430280758764&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649 )
and I made couple of tests to see what is the best shape / cheep as materials....
Along with my best friend GLENN Cullip - all Credits to him , we came up with this model of boss showing here .
I used
PLA 1,75mm /
,20 layer high /
,8 shell thickness & bottom / top layers
45 C for the bed /
200 C for the extruder /
infill 15% /
40% Printing speed /

description.text:
This is a simple Foxeer Mini mount for all those simple X frames with a standoff spacing of 30.5 x 30.5 mm (flight controller pattern).

V2 has some ziptie slots in case you want to hold any component outside the quad (e.x.Rx, VTx,...)

I have some 3/4" EMT Conduit tubing laying around my house which I will be using for making a snow cab for my riding mower. The EMT Conduit is very strong and much can be done with it outside its original purpose of running electrical wire in it!

I have searched around for some fittings and was not having much luck so I designed some fittings that I have not yet printed but intend to as we approach the end of summer and into fall.

The parts I designed are what I believe I will need to use to build the tractor snow cab but as I start designing that project and if I realize I need something else for the EMT conduit then I will add it to this thing listing.

Each fitting has a 1/4" hole that is intended to be used to bolt the EMT in the fitting by drilling a hole in the EMT and passing a bolt through the fitting and conduit.

For those that may not understand the intended purpose...these fittings are not for use as electrical conduit fittings to run electricity with! they are more for making structural items out of the conduit combined with these fittings.

I have included the STL files as well as the original 123d Design files so you may modify as you desire.

I intend on printing these in PLA with anywhere from 60~100% infill. Should be able to print without supports or raft. I will probably print the prototypes at low res and 30% and go from there and will revise this as needed.

UPDATE: Added two more parts.

UPDATE: I started printing and at 30% I feel these might be very strong for the purpose I intend on using them. I will continue adding photos and updates as I proceed further.

Update - 08/25/2017: I fit some conduit in the parts I printed. They are really tight so I suggest you increase the part size a bit when you slice. I will be testing with another single part and will advise what to increase to (percentage). I believe I will test by increasing by 3% when I do. I added some photos of the parts with the conduit pushed on.

Update - 09/15/2017: I printed some 45's and increased their size by 5% and they fit easily onto the 3/4 conduit. It might be too loose for some but it will work for my application. Next time I will print at 3% increase and see what that gets me.

Update - 09/17/2017: I printed some TEE's and increased the size by 4% and still an easy fit on the 3/4 conduit so now my next print will be 3% increase as I think that will be the magic number.

Girlfriend wanted something to use for traveling with smaller amounts of cosmetics. This is modeled after some of what she has laying around.  
Parts are threaded and have tolerances to fit (IIRC it was 0.50mm part to part and 0.25mm thread to thread, since the thread and body were toleranced at different points during modeling). Every print I've made requires a few turns in and out to "break in" the threads before use but once they work they work well.
I kept the infill relatively low (15%) and used standard (2) shells, but I did print them with 0.15mm and 0.13mm layer heights to keep the inside surface as smooth as possible.

title: Hypercube Magnetic Quick Mount Printhead X Carriage

description.text:
Hey there,

I present my very quick mountable Hypercube magnetic printhead. I personally use it with a lot of different nozzle diameters and V6/vulcano setups. Since you are changing the whole printhead you need following components for each head:

  • E3D Hotend full kit
  • Radial Fan
  • Cooling Fan
  • Bed Level Sensor

Dowel Pins
M4 screws are used to mount the E3D Mount centered to the carriage and transmit sideways forces.

Mount the Magnets
Purchase some magnets anywhere, e.g. from Banggood. The magnets shall be glued in. Consider PETG does not bond to glue so good. PLA shall be a better option in this case. I suggest to orient the magnets with alternating polarities. Additionally I added some tape to the magnet's surface to protect them from damage but this is optional.

Materials you need
Electrics

  • D-Sub 9 Female for the printer side
  • D-Sub 9 Male for the printhead side

X Carriage

  • 8x Neodymium Magnets (d=12x2mm)
  • 11x M3 Nuts
  • 11x M3x10 Screws
  • 2x M4 Nuts
  • 2x M4x10 Screws

E3D Mount

  • 8x Neodynmium Magnets (d=12x2mm)
  • 2x M3x10
  • 2x M3x16
  • 1x M3x20

You can find my pinout for a d-sub 9 connector in the download section.

Looking for a Fan Duct with Sensor Mount?
E3D V6 https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1796964
E3D Vulcano https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2433892

Some further Improvement Ideas
An integrated electric connection with pogo pins would be worth a remix. The source files are for Design Spark Mechanical

title: Height Guide / Pinda Sensor Level Help

description.text:
This is a stepped Guide to help me level my Pinda Sensor up/down.

To Level it up just move it onto the 0 Plate, loosen it, move it onto the plate with the height difference you want to move up and screw tight again.
To move down level it to one of the plates that has a difference you want to move it down, loosen it and drop it onto the 0 plate, tighten it and done.

description.text:
Bearing Housing for- 10mm & 12mm Linear Bearings- ( SCS-UU )

Bearing Position & Mounting Holes are in the same place as the Aluminium Housings,,, they are designed to Reduce the weight of the MainBed,,,

Square M3 Nuts are used on both the 10mm & 12m and theirs a Hex Nut Version for the 12mm --

Mounting holes are 3mm Diameter,,

The parts fit together perfectly – they have a 0.2mm offset and the corners have been recessed so Corner swell is not a problem a 0.5mm Bevelled edge is on the Inside Clamp edge so first layer Flashing is not a problem either,,,– No clean-up or Very little is needed depending on your printing quality– they have been printed and tested a Dozen times

12mm or 1/2 Inch 4 gauge Pan Head screws should be used on the sides of the Bearing Holder but M3 Bolt or even Glue or Thermal Weld can be used and 3/8 inch or up to 10mm on the topside of the 10mm Version

There’s the bearing Spec Sheet which I used for a reference include with the download ---
Heat the 4-gauge Screw Tips with a flame for a clean thread cut,,
SketchUp Files is included for Mod work

description.text:
This is a simple fairlead for the Axial Wraith. Mainly applicable if using a servo winch setup. Designed around the stock servo on axle setup, I have not tested with a CMS setup, and I don't have any interest in putting CMS on my Wraith at this time.

To use, I highly recommend drilling out the mounting holes on the wraith to 3.0mm. I don't recommend 1/8", If you don't have a drill bit, just use a 3mm screw and strip the hole out completely.

There are 2 version. The first version is if you have removed the stock front bumper light buckets. The second version moves the fairlead back, and makes it more narrow to allow the use of the light buckets.

You will need to change screws to mount this:
No-lights: M3x8
Lights: M3x12

The screws will cut their own threads into the fairlead holes, DO NOT OVER TIGHTEN. If you are an extreme user feel free to use longer screws and locknuts.

title: Mini Rack for Single Board Computers

description.text:
I figured if your going to build a raspberry pi supper computer, why not build it in style....

This is very much a work in progress. Right now. The basic rails, couplers, and side panels are complete and working well. All holes are threaded for standard #6-32 computer screws. But may practical parts are still missing. (IE the actual board cases).

This project was intended as a Raspberry Pi cluster case, but when defining the Mini Rack Unit specification allowances were made for most single board computer and micro controller boards currently available. There were a few single board computers that are just too big to be practical.

Each rack is 7MU (minirack Units) tall. You can make larger racks using the included coupler to vertically connect two racks. You will need at least a 180mm bead for the basic rack (side rails can be printed diagonally). Some parts (like the side panel) will require a larger build platform.

1MU is defined as 99mm Wide 24mm Tall and no more than 150 mm Deep. There are three mounting Holes on each side of the rack. The Mounting holes are 105mm apart horizontally, and placed vertically at 4mm 12mm, and 20mm. The rails themselves are designed to allow .5mm above, bellow, and on ether side of the case (actual clearance is 100mm x 25mm).

To do:
Design single board computer cases to populate the rack
Design horizontal coupler to connect racks side by side
Build plates for interconnect (keystone for Ethernet, or power barrel connectors for example).

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.1 This works great for me when using threaded holes

Notes:

All parts have been designed so they can be arranged on the build plate without the need of supports.
This design has rather tight tolerances, and was designed for use with PLA. Some modification may be required to work with other materials.

For a basic rack you will need to print
2 "TopBottom_Ring_V3.stl"
4 "Mini-Rack_Side_Rail_V2.stl"

You Will Need
24 #6-32 computer screws

The holes will print threaded, so you should only need to remove any stringing from the holes before assembly.

Place one rail in a corner of one of the TobBotom rings, there are tabs to hold it in place. There will be some overhang on the front and back but will be flush when the rack is populated.
Secure the rail in place using 3 screws
Add 3 more rails and secure them before attaching the second topbotom ring.

comments.text:
Suggestion:
Could you design rack mounts for 2.5 inch storage devices? It would be great if single board clusters can mount external disk drives without having to prepare a separate HDD rack adjacent to your singleboard computer rack.

title: UMO / UM2 - Experimental Vibration dampening foots
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a dampening foot with flexible infill made to work as a spring.

I made this to cut the vibration from one printer to the other since I was getting artifacts on top layers.

I use S3D with 5 process, one for each object. This allows the user to customize the Perimeters of each part. All parts except the top part go with 0 infill.

ALSO. Step file is available for anyone to change or remix this for their printer.

VERY IMPORTANT

The FFF S3D factory file is the one I use for my printer, it has my start sequence, prime sequence (quite nice btw) But all is optimized for 1.75mm with a GudoZGE direct drive, so PLEASE remember to use the FFF just as A GUIDE ONLY of what I did.

On Cura this can be done too, but since the UI on (current at the moment of posting this 2.6 version) doesn't allow to select objects that are 'inside' other objects, you will have to choose Per Object Settings with all the objects apart and then Merge them, so they have the proper position.

On S3D the middle and top are lowered by 0.1-0.2 because S3D goes bananas sometimes when doing jobs with different heights.

Thanks to IRobertI and Gudo for the input and ideas to make this better.

UMO+ UM2 Hotned + GudoZGE + 1.75mod

author: Hooka

description.text:
The famous BT331 armoured vehicle (although technically an armoured car, common current definition regards all wheeled and tracked armoured vehicles as "tanks"), is represented in this replica. Based on two Smith and Westor nuke generators, feeding two shield generators, both sets fully linked, it is a fast and well protected tank. The inclusion of the airlock (on the left hand side) also means it can work in hostile environments. The armament on the Type A was a 102mm Nuke cannon linked with a laser beam gun system. This proved problematic in combat which led to it being replaced on the Type B with 2 122mm nuke slug cannons. Without the lazer cannon, all power could be used for movement and defense, which proved useful. However the last version of the early turret, the Type C kept a 122mm cannon and added back the laser cannon, which was useful against certain well shielded targets. The guns can fire either a nuke warhead (although only 4 are commonly carried), Berkelian Darts (of which 30 are normally carried), and HE rounds (commonly 30 also carried).
Used extensively by the Federation, they were a major part of the great counter-attack throughout the Beta Hydra system during the War of Almai Independence, replacing earlier BT700 vehicles.
Some of these vehicles are built in the outer rim independent states, and some were even captured by Alien forces, and some reports indicate some were even converted for Alien crew and used against the Almai and Federation forces.
When the new turret was designed, it proved expensive to upgrade all current existing vehicles, so as a stopgap a turret extension was designed and added to the earlier turrets. This upgrade allowed more ammunition and a longer range communication focus to be carried.
The type d featured a new three 142mm multi firing cannons which can be loaded with nuke warheads, HE, proximity AA, and Berkelium AT dart rounds. The 142mm cannons are an improvement over the 122mm and have almost twice the range of the 102mm guns. No laser guns are carried on this version which directs all nuclear power to the twin linked shields and for movement.
The tank is commonly known as the Beech which is a reference to the tree like growths on Nike III where the tank was first tested.
